explanation:
For deciding whether any code in lfs_dir_traverse is dead (can be removed without changing observable behaviour) the next analysis needs the following additional symbols and why:

- LFS_DIR_TRAVERSE_DEPTH: size of the explicit stack; required to determine whether the LFS_ASSERT(sp < ...) branch can fire or whether stack overflows are possible (affects reachability and side-effects).

- struct lfs_dir_traverse: layout and semantics of fields saved/restored on the stack (dir, off, ptag, attrs, attrcount, tmask, ttag, begin, end, diff, cb, data, tag, buffer, disk). Needed to know what state is preserved across the explicit recursion and whether popping/pushing yields side-effects that would make code removal observable.

- lfs_t, lfs_mdir_t, struct lfs_mattr, struct lfs_diskoff, struct lfs_attr, lfs_off_t, lfs_tag_t: all type definitions and struct field names used by the function (e.g. dir->off, dir->pair[0], disk.block/off, attr.tag/buffer, attr[i].type/size/buffer). These are required to reason about pointer reads/writes, aliasing, and whether operations (reads, buffer usages) have effects that would make code non-dead.

- LFS_MKTAG: macro that composes tags. Required to reason about the tag filtering logic, comparisons (masking), and constructed tags used for recursion and callback calls; affects whether branches are taken and whether removing code changes tag semantics.

- LFS_FROM_NOOP, LFS_FROM_MOVE, LFS_FROM_USERATTRS, LFS_TYPE_USERATTR, LFS_TYPE_STRUCT: tag/type constants used in switch/if logic. Needed to determine which branches (noop, move, userattrs, normal) are possible and whether those branches are relevant (i.e. removable) for any input.

- LFS_ASSERT: its semantics (no-op vs abort vs logging) matter. If LFS_ASSERT can abort, the asserted condition is observable behaviour; thus code that leads to the assert is not dead. Must know how it is defined in the project.

- lfs_dir_traverse_filter: the function pointer compared against cb and assigned as cb when recursing. Needed because equality/comparison of function pointers affects the special-case skip for LFS_FROM_MOVE, and the filter's behaviour (return values/side-effects) determines whether replacing/removing recursion would change behaviour.

- lfs_bd_read (semantics): although present in the call graph, the analysis requires its detailed behaviour: when it returns errors, whether it has side-effects (caching, device state), and its return-value conventions. The early return on err makes some paths observable; knowing whether lfs_bd_read can fail or mutate state is necessary to decide if the surrounding code is removable.

- lfs_frombe32 (semantics): transforms on-tag values (endian swap) affect the computed tag (and ptag xor). Understanding its exact behaviour is necessary to tell whether computed tags can equal particular constants and thus whether branches (and their bodies) can actually affect behaviour.

Note: the call-graph already lists the direct callees used for tag decomposition (lfs_tag_dsize, lfs_tag_id, lfs_tag_type3, lfs_tag_size). Those functions/macros' actual semantics are also important and should be included in the analysis input (they are already in the call graph). The symbols above are the additional type/constants/macros and the two function semantics (lfs_bd_read, lfs_frombe32) that must be known to determine if any code paths in lfs_dir_traverse are dead.
